//This master thesis researches a new way of making in architecture: 
 In #experiment01-Triangular-Vault[section-3] the feasibility of using snow as formwork material is tested. #experiment02-Happy-Accidents[section-5] explores possibilities and chance of shaping with snow. The technical advantages are analysed in #experiment03-Melt-Out[section-7]. In field trips to #research-Heinz-Isler[section-9] the history of natural form finding is explored. Concrete behaviour in cold environments is tested in the #experiment04-Concrete-Laboratory[section-11]. Inaccuracies of snow as formwork material are taken into account in #experiment05-Curtain-Arch[section-13]. #experiment06-1-to-100[section-15] explores a manual way for producing digitally. The process is executed in #experiment07-Shell-at-a-Rock[section-17]. Possibilities are taken further at #experiment08-Glaspass[section-19]. A summary about #Natural-Formations[section-21]. Previous structural knowledge with ice was gained in #The-Ice-Shell-Project[section-23]. #About[section-25] the participants. 
 See the story in the #movie-The-Accurate-Inaccurate[section-2]//
